betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Just chop down a few trees for right now, you'll need quite a bit of wood to help you get started.

While you're at it, get some saplings and re-plant the trees. #TeamTrees!

Seems pretty easy, just some dirt.

(Very good quest reward, I know.)

You need some gravel to make some flint for some basic tools. Search around for some.

Flint §cdoes not §0§fnaturally drop, and needs to be crafted. Clicking on an item in the quest book will show its crafting recipe.

You need some basic tools to get started, GregTech tools are primarily used during the whole pack. Start out now with a simple flint pickaxe to mine and a sword to kill some enemies at night.

§9Note that GregTech shows several recipes due to it being part of the same crafting ID. For the most part, it can be ignored, most of the tools are made the same way.

Make a crafting table. Pretty necessary if you ask me.

This is the point where I tell you to look at JEI. All. The. Time. JEI in this pack is your best friend, it tells you all the recipes and gives you necessary information about machines. It also lets you just click the little plus to do crafting recipes aswell. Clicking on an item in this questbook will show you its recipe in JEI aswell, so use that to your advantage. Also, you can click "A" (default key) to bookmark an item in the top-left of JEI. Will help you remember what you need to make.
Just some basic building blocks for you to use.
Some extra tools which could help you.
Go mine some stone, you'll need a bit.

Obviously, furnaces are pretty helpful in the making of ingots. And, well, you obviously need ingots. Obviously.

It's also... a lot... of cobblestone... sorry not sorry
Yep. There's no stone tools. You'll be stuck with at best iron until a lot later on. Sorry?

Veins are generally very large and rare in here with the ocassional ore. Along some of your cobblestone mining, you may have noticed some spots on the surface. They're generally right above one of these huge ore veins. JEI will tell you where these veins spawn, and yes, some of them do spawn in only space!
No charcoal, not yet. Charcoal is made inside the coke oven later on.

Make some okay(-ish) food through your furnace. You should know what to do, right?

§5§5§4§3§5...right?

What's the difference between cobblestone and stone? I don't know, one looks a little more in shambles than the other. Anyway, get yourself some stone. Good for some GT tools.

Also looks pretty okay-ish for some building blocks.

A mortar makes life easier for you with flint. Like the flint pickaxe, it shows multiple recipes, but the middle ingots can just be replaces with (almost) any GT material and work, including flint.

§3After this quest, the quests will start saying "Darmstadium," it will be the exact same as this though, just with the flexability to do which ever material you want.§3§3§m I'm also incredibly lazy, its getting tiring to make the tool every single time.

Just a challenge. See if you could do it!

§6Not required for progression.
Will be helpful later on, better to make some now while you have a bit of stone on hand.
Get some seeds to plant, gonna be helpful for that nutrition you gotta keep up.

A boatload of wood to make a boatload of boats to hold your boatload of wood to make boatloads of boats to hold your boatloads of boats... you know what, i'll just stop. Just a challenge for you to do made easier by your nifty new axe.

§6Not required, but can be helpful later on.

Just a challenge, made a little bit easier by your new shovel.

§6Not required for progression, but could be helpful.

§§§lI AM NOT A MORON!

§rI mean, uh, get yourself some wheat!

Making bread is not the same, you gotta do several processes before you can get that delicious bread.

§6Note that some parts probably can't be done right now, progress on for now.

While there are other veins which give you iron, one of the easiest ones to find will give you magnetite, an ore which can be smelted into iron. Look for the pieces on the surface to help you find a vein.

As a bonus, this vein also gives vanadium magnetite, an important ore for later on, and gold. Also gives a slight bit of normal iron ore.

§nIt is §b§nHIGHLY§b§n§n§r§n recommended you mark down any vein you come across with JourneyMap, the default key is "J"

There are several other sources of iron, such as yellow & brown limonite or banded iron. They all give just about the same thing, iron ingots. Where these veins differ however is that they are much more dense but much rarer.

This is the steam tier, where the "real fun" begins.

§4Be prepared to lose your whole life to this, seriously. GregTech is a vast mod when combined with Shadows Of Greg. You will spend hours on this part alone, hours on every voltage tier.
Make yourself some iron by throwing that ore into a furnace.
This quest leads to other veins which may be required for steam.

Copper Ore is also quite important for numerous things.

Chalcopyrite Veins are probably your best bet, as they also give some iron.
You can get some gold ore by processing the gold ore (duh)
Tin is quite an important ore. Best find yourself a vein right now.

Another source of copper, except this one is very deep and rare. But is almost exclusively copper, all the way through.

§7§6Also note that there ARE NO surface indicators of this vein. May be very difficult to find!

Tetrahedrite is another source of copper. This vein is almost excusively copper.

Is also a good source of stibnite, a very important ore later on. However, this ore cannot be processed right now.

Also only spawns in mountains.

Bronze is a really important material for making steam machines.

Bronze for now can be made by crushing down copper and tin into their dust forms, then recombining them in a 3 copper to 1 tin ratio in a crafting grid. The result is bronze dust, which can then be smelted into bronze.

§nThis is the only way to make bronze for a little while, and it is slightly innefficient. Try to change over to a different way later on!

Gregtech has a whole host of tools that you'll need, like the hammer and wrench. Remember that all of these can be made with different materials, however, your best option right now is iron. (Bronze is weaker.)

The first one you'll need is the hammer for the creation of plates.
Bronze isn't good on its own, you'll need to make it into plates!
Iron plates are necessary for numerous items, including other GT tools.
The wrench is vital to many recipes! Again, its best to make this out of iron for now.
Make yourself a file. Gonna come in handy for rods!
You're gonna need a few of these... for more GT tools!
Bronze rods will be pretty good for some Gregtech machines and multiblocks later on.
Some tin will be necessary for bronze, some more tin for some other stuff.
Copper is a necessary material for bronze, as well as some other stuff.
A saw is helpful for making wood more efficiently.
Who knew that a screw could drive? I don't know, but regardless, you'll need a screwdriver.
A crowbar will remove covers from machines via a simple right click; not helpful to you for a little while but will be helpful so you won't have to break machines.
These will be helpful for the creation of some items, like buckets.

Let me guess, you want the bucket, don't you?

Make yourself some curved plates and make it then.
Iron rings are gonna be helpful for chests.
Bolts can be turned to screws, just one of the many items you'll need.
Screws are used in numerous different recipes.
You can finally make a damn chest! They're, however, a very big pain to craft. Sorry, not sorry.
Whatever this is, you can go ahead and craft it if you like.
Used to make fluid pipes, you'll surely need a lot of these.

Bronze fluid pipes move fluids, like steam, around at a reasonable rate. They're also used to make the steam machines!

Try to invest some time into making these right now, you're gonna make a lot.
That's right, you spent all this time in a steam quest line to just now make the thing that will even make steam.

betterquesting:10.name:8: A few things to know before you start on steam...
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
§n§c§nDO NOT:

§r- Refill the boiler while it is hot and empty on water, this includes pumping water into it automatically.
- Let the boiler run out of water while it is hot
- Keep the boiler on for an extended period of time
- Give the boiler life advice

§c§nFAILING TO NOT DO ANY OF THESE (except for maybe that last one) WILL MOST DEFINETLY RESULT IN A VERY LOUD BOOM.

§r§6Also note that water IS NOT infinite, not anywhere. You'll get something later on that'll collect water, but that may be a little while. If I were you, settle down next to an ocean or find one.

Coal ore is well... used for coal. What did you expect, some kind of long explanation?

Lignite from these veins is §oin my opinion §rcompletely useless for the most part.
A steam furnace will work like a normal furnace, except it uses steam.
Machine casings are integral to almost all machines in Gregtech. For a little while, this'll be your best casing, as it will be used to make almost all the steam machines.
Clay is going to be a large necessity for steam, so you'll need quite a bit.
No Description

For bricks, you're gonna need a brick mold.

You only are going to need one (assuming you don't lose it in a mess of chests)
Unfired clay is a necessity towards bricks, obviously.
Bricks are made by throwing that unfired clay into a furnace.
Bricks are a bit of a process, you need some water to make them.
The alloy furnace will §oalloy §ryou to make new alloys, and make bronze a little more efficient.

The macerator will be rather important to macerate down items, and can double ores.

§6Note that you cannot have something blocking the back, including pipes.

Make a boatload of bronze, you're gonna need a lot for machines!

Bronze can now be made in the alloy smelter with 3 copper and 1 tin, and can be either their dust forms or normal ingots. It is §ahighly §rrecommended you use this way to make bronze from now on, as it is the most efficient way to make bronze.

Macerating ores §cis not §rrecommended, at least not yet. The steam macerator takes an obsurd amount of time to macerate ores (40 seconds EACH!) and gives no biproducts like you see in JEI.

But, if you want to follow this quest (because, why not?) and macerate your ores, by all means, go ahead.

You can macerate down the ore into the crushed variant, then macerate it again (or combine it with a hammer in a crafting grid) and turn it into its impure variant. The impure variant can be smelted down in a furnace to be turned to iron.
Flint dust is the second component of making glass early on. It can be made by simply throwing some flint into your macerator.
Glass is made by smelting glass dust in a furnace. Glass is used for several things, including tanks and parts of multiblocks which we may be about to get into§o hint hint§r.
The compressor will compress things. Is that not obvious by its name?

The piston is a quite import-- wait no, this is a vanilla piston isn't it? This piston will mainly be used in steam machines but nearly no where else. But it does make for some cool doors if you want to try and make one.

But the main use for you right now is that this will be used in the making of machines like the compressor or the forge hammer. (P.S you can make these a whole hell of a lot easier when you get the compressor.)

There are several different tanks you can make, some you may even be able to make right now, but the main one you want is the bronze tank, it stores a decent amount of liquid and is going to be used here in a little bit ;)

§0for some odd reason, i feel like that recipe should break the glass that it uses, so uhh...

Wrought iron is just iron but on drugs. Most of the tools can be made with wrought iron, and its going to be your best material for quite some time.

Wrought Iron is made by smelting down iron nuggets and compressing them. Iron nuggets, however, are a bit more complicated. There's a few ways you can make them, either by macerating down yellow/brown limonite ore or pyrite ore and smelting the final §rdust. Later on when steel is aquired, you can make iron nuggets in the alloy smelter with the nugget mold and some iron.
Iron blocks are helpful for anvils, which you will need for your next machine.
You can repair your items in here, and you'll need an anvil for the forge hammer. I recommend you make two, but one will do for the forge hammer.

The forge hammer allows the creation of plates to be significantly more efficient than crafting them, instead of a 2:1 (ingot:plate), it will now be a 3:2 (ingot:plate) ratio. Is also used for some other things, like crushing ores down to their impure piles much faster than the macerator.

§4Note that while you can crush down ores to their crushed versions in the forge hammer, it DOES NOT double.§r

The most usefull thing the forge hammer does for you right now is creating plates much more efficiently. You should be using the forge hammer from now on until you reach another machine which will make your ingot:plate ratio a staggering §l1:1!§r

For now though, make some plates for you to use in the long run.
Equiped with your new forge hammer, process up some wrought iron plates with the wrought iron you made a bit ago.

betterquesting:10.name:8: Your First Multiblock: The Coke Oven
betterquesting:10.desc:8: The coke oven is used to turn coal into coal coke, as well as make charcoal. But one of its best uses is making creosote, which is helpful as a fuel and for a few crafting recipes.
The extractor will be a helpful machine for rubber later on.

The lava boiler is just like your regular old boiler, except it runs off of lava! If you have a stable source of lava, like a underground pool of lava, or you have nether access, this thing is great! If you don't, then uh... don't make this.
Coal coke is a better version of coal, made in the coke oven. Simply throw coal coke into the coke oven, and boom! §oAfter about 5 years atleast...§r
For a silver vien, the best you got is a galena vein. This vein also gives lead, which could be helpful later on. Unfortunately, galena is unable to be processed until a much later stage.
The solar boiler will generate steam when supplied with water and a constant line above it to the sun.

You can make almost all your GregTech tools out of wrought iron, including things like your pickaxe or hammer. Wrought Iron is significantly more durable than anything you've had thus far, and so it would work great as a material.

It is only slightly worse, however, than iron in some stats. Its a very worth it trade off though if you ask me.

You're gonna need a lot of brick dust for the Primitive Blast Furnace, which is your first way to make steel here.

(I'm not even sure if this is enough...)

A lot of clay dust is also going to be required for the Primitive Blast Furnace (PBF)

(I don't even know if this is enough...)

Fireclay is one of the main things used in the PBF build to make the bricks as well as the controller. Unfortunately, you're gonna need to process it a little bit before you get to there.

(Again, I have no idea if this is enough, you should try to make extra.)
Now you're getting somewhere with this! §oBut you're not even half way there... you should again try to make a lot of extra of these, even if you have extra at the end.§r
The very start of your journey.
Goes over the Steam part of GregTech
